          "input": {
            "command": "cat >> /home/shako/REPOS/Indie-Hacking/deepagents/deepagents-cli-course.html << 'HTMLEOF'\n\n<!-- MODULE 2: Meet the Actors -->\n<section class=\"module module--warm\" id=\"module-2\">\n  <div class=\"module__inner\">\n\n    <div class=\"module__header animate-in\">\n      <div class=\"module__number\">Module 2</div>\n      <h1 class=\"module__title\">Meet the Actors</h1>\n      <p class=\"module__subtitle\">Eight key characters work together to make this tool run. Knowing who does what helps you tell the AI where to put things.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 1: Actor map -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">The cast of characters</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">Think of the CLI as a movie production. Each \"actor\" has a specific role. When you talk to the AI, you're directing the whole cast — but the AI needs to know which role to assign each task.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"pattern-cards\">\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🎬</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">main.py</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">The director. Decides whether to launch the interactive app or handle a subcommand like <code>list</code> or <code>reset</code>. Runs first, exits fast.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🖥️</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">app.py</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">The stage manager. Runs the Textual TUI — the interactive window, the chat history, the input box. Keeps everything rendered on screen.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🤖</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">agent.py</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">The producer. Builds the AI agent — wires up the language model, tools, memory, and middleware. The architect of what the AI can do.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🔌</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">textual_adapter.py</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">The translator. Converts between Textual UI events and LangGraph agent commands. Handles streaming, interrupts, and the approval menu.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">⚙️</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">config.py</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">The stage crew. Handles settings, API keys, glyphs (symbols for the UI), and shell command allow-lists. Everything the app needs to know about its environment.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🛠️</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">tools.py</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">The toolbox. Provides the agent's web search (via Tavily) and URL fetching tools. Optional — only active if API keys are configured.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🧠</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">skills/</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">The rehearsal notes. Skills are like custom instructions that augment the AI — extra capabilities you can load from files on disk. The <span class=\"term\" data-tip=\"Middleware sits between the AI model and the tool layer, intercepting and potentially modifying requests and responses.\">middleware</span> loads and manages them.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">📝</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">command_registry.py</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">The teleprompter. Defines all slash commands (<code>/clear</code>, <code>/model</code>, <code>/threads</code>, etc.) and their priority tiers — which ones can interrupt the AI mid-thought.</div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 2: Group chat -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">How the actors talk to each other</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">When you type a message, here's which actors exchange information.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"group-chat\">\n        <div class=\"group-chat__header\">\n          <span>🔄</span>\n          <span>Actor communication — \"user asks to reset an agent\"</span>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"group-chat__body\">\n          <div class=\"chat-bubble chat-bubble--left\">\n            <div class=\"chat-bubble__sender\">main.py</div>\n            Sees <code>--agent coder</code> flag. Passes to <code>cli_main()</code>.\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"chat-bubble chat-bubble--left\">\n            <div class=\"chat-bubble__sender\">agent.py</div>\n            <code>reset_agent()</code> reads the target agent's <code>AGENTS.md</code>. Deletes and recreates the directory.\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"chat-bubble chat-bubble--left\">\n            <div class=\"chat-bubble__sender\">config.py</div>\n            Provides the agent directory path via <code>settings.user_deepagents_dir</code>.\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"chat-bubble chat-bubble--center\">\n            No AI involved at all! This is pure file I/O.\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--accent mt-8\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">🎯</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">Why this matters for prompting AI</div>\n          When you say \"reset the coder agent,\" the AI doesn't do the reset — it delegates to <code>agent.py</code>'s <code>reset_agent()</code> function. If you want to customize <em>how</em> the reset works, you'd edit that function, not ask the AI to \"be better at resetting agents.\"\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 3: Quiz -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Check your understanding</h2>\n\n      <div class=\"quiz\" id=\"quiz-module-2\">\n        <div class=\"quiz__question\">You want to add a new slash command like <code>/build</code> that runs a build. Which file do you need to change?</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__options\">\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"a\">agent.py — that's where all the logic lives</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"b\" data-correct=\"true\">command_registry.py — that's where slash commands are defined</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"c\">app.py — that's where the UI handles user input</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"d\">config.py — that's where all settings live</button>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--correct\" data-for=\"b\">Right! Slash commands are declared as <code>SlashCommand</code> entries in <code>command_registry.py</code>. Each entry specifies the name, description, and <em>bypass tier</em> (whether it can interrupt the AI mid-task).</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"a\">Not quite — agent.py builds the agent graph but doesn't define UI commands. Slash commands are registered in <code>command_registry.py</code>.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"c\">Close, but app.py handles the UI presentation of slash commands, not their definition. You define them in <code>command_registry.py</code>.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"d\">config.py handles settings and configuration, not command definitions. Slash commands go in <code>command_registry.py</code>.</div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!-- MODULE 3: How the Pieces Talk -->\n<section class=\"module\" id=\"module-3\">\n  <div class=\"module__inner\">\n\n    <div class=\"module__header animate-in\">\n      <div class=\"module__number\">Module 3</div>\n      <h1 class=\"module__title\">How the Pieces Talk</h1>\n      <p class=\"module__subtitle\">Data flows through the system in predictable patterns. Understanding the flow helps you debug \"why isn't X showing up?\"</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 1: Message queue -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">The message queue — traffic control for the AI</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">Imagine the AI as a busy executive. If five people send messages at once, they don't all interrupt — they wait in a queue. The AI processes them one at a time.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--info mb-6\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">🚦</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">The metaphor: an air traffic controller</div>\n          When planes line up to land, the controller doesn't let them all descend at once — they stack in a queue and get clearance one at a time. The message queue works the same way: it keeps requests orderly and prevents the AI from getting overwhelmed.\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"step-cards\">\n        <div class=\"step-card\">\n          <div class=\"step-card__num\">1</div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__title\">You type a message</div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__desc\">The Textual input widget captures it and submits it to the app's message bus.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"step-card\">\n          <div class=\"step-card__num\">2</div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__title\">The queue decides priority</div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__desc\">Some messages are <span class=\"term\" data-tip=\"Commands that run no matter what the AI is doing — like /quit. They bypass the queue entirely.\">always-bypass</span> (<code>/quit</code>). Others are <span class=\"term\" data-tip=\"Commands that must wait until the AI is idle — like /clear or /remember.\">queued</span> (<code>/clear</code>). The queue classifies each message and either lets it through immediately or makes it wait.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"step-card\">\n          <div class=\"step-card__num\">3</div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__title\">The agent processes one at a time</div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__desc\">While the agent is thinking or running tools, new messages wait. Once the agent is idle, the next message is pulled from the queue.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 2: HITL flow -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">The Human-in-the-Loop safety valve</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">Before the AI can run certain \"dangerous\" operations — writing files, running shell commands, searching the web — it pauses and asks your permission. This is called <abbr class=\"term\" data-tip=\"HITL = Human in the Loop. A design pattern where an AI pauses before sensitive actions and asks a human for approval.\">HITL</abbr>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"data-flow\">\n        <div class=\"data-flow__track\" style=\"justify-content: center; gap: 16px;\">\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-1);\">🤖</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">Agent</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-arrow\" style=\"position:relative;flex:none;width:40px;\"></div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-3);\">🛑</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">HITL Interrupt</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-arrow\" style=\"position:relative;flex:none;width:40px;\"></div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-2);\">👤</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">You (approve/reject)</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-arrow\" style=\"position:relative;flex:none;width:40px;\"></div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-5);\">⚡</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">Tool executes</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--accent\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">🔐</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">What gets gated?</div>\n          Shell commands (<code>execute</code>), file writes/edits (<code>write_file</code>, <code>edit_file</code>), web search, URL fetching, and subagent delegation are all behind the HITL gate. If you run with <code>-y</code> / <code>--auto-approve</code>, all gates open automatically.\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 3: Middleware pipeline -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">The middleware pipeline</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">Middleware is like a series of filters that every AI request and response passes through. Each one can inspect, modify, or act on the data.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"translation-block\">\n        <div class=\"translation-block__header\">How middleware is stacked (simplified from agent.py)</div>\n        <div class=\"translation-block__grid\">\n          <div class=\"translation-block__code\">\n<pre class=\"code-pre\"><div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">1</span><span>agent_middleware = []</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">2</span><span>agent_middleware.append(ConfigurableModelMiddleware())</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">3</span><span>agent_middleware.append(AskUserMiddleware())   # ← AI asks you questions</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">4</span><span>agent_middleware.append(MemoryMiddleware())     # ← persistent memory</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">5</span><span>agent_middleware.append(SkillsMiddleware())    # ← loaded skills</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">6</span><span>agent_middleware.append(LocalContextMiddleware) # ← git info, file tree</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">7</span><span>agent_middleware.append(SummarizationMiddleware) # ← context window management</div></pre>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"translation-block__english\">\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 1</strong> — Start with an empty list of middleware.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 2</strong> — <strong>ConfigurableModel</strong>: wraps the language model so it can be swapped or configured at runtime.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 3</strong> — <strong>AskUser</strong>: gives the AI a tool to ask <em>you</em> clarifying questions mid-task.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 4</strong> — <strong>Memory</strong>: loads persistent context from <code>AGENTS.md</code> files so the AI remembers past conversations.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 5</strong> — <strong>Skills</strong>: injects custom instructions from skill files on disk.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 6</strong> — <strong>LocalContext</strong>: provides git branch, directory tree, and project info to the AI.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 7</strong> — <strong>Summarization</strong>: compresses old messages when the context window gets full.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--info\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">🧩</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">Middleware ordering matters</div>\n          Each middleware sees the output of the one before it. Memory is added before Skills so that skill loading can reference memories. AskUser is added early so its tool is available for the whole conversation.\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 4: Quiz -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Check your understanding</h2>\n\n      <div class=\"quiz\" id=\"quiz-module-3\">\n        <div class=\"quiz__question\">A user reports: \"I asked the AI to search for something but it just ignored my message.\" What might be happening?</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__options\">\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"a\">The web search tool isn't installed</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"b\">The message is sitting in the queue waiting for the AI to finish its current task</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"c\">The AI decided not to use the search tool this time</button>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--correct\" data-for=\"b\">Right! The message queue is working as designed — if the AI is currently running a tool or thinking, new messages wait in the queue. This is the \"traffic control\" behavior from this module.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"a\">Possible, but the more likely explanation is the queue — the AI might be busy with a previous request.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"c\">The AI can choose not to use a tool, but it would at least respond to your message explaining why. If the message was silently ignored, it's likely queued.</div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!-- MODULE 4: The Outside World -->\n<section class=\"module module--warm\" id=\"module-4\">\n  <div class=\"module__inner\">\n\n    <div class=\"module__header animate-in\">\n      <div class=\"module__number\">Module 4</div>\n      <h1 class=\"module__title\">The Outside World</h1>\n      <p class=\"module__subtitle\">The CLI doesn't run in isolation — it talks to language models, external APIs, MCP servers, and optional sandbox clouds.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 1: Models -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Language models — the brain</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">The AI \"brain\" isn't running on your machine — it's a remote <span class=\"term\" data-tip=\"An API hosted by a company (like Anthropic, OpenAI, or Google) that runs AI models. You send text, it sends back text.\">language model API</span>. The CLI supports multiple providers.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grid-3 mb-6\">\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🧠</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">Anthropic Claude</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Set <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code>. Specify model with <code>--model anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-6</code>.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🤖</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">OpenAI GPT</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Set <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code>. Specify with <code>--model gpt-4o</code>.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🌴</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">Google Gemini</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Set <code>GOOGLE_API_KEY</code> or use Vertex AI via <code>GOOGLE_CLOUD_PROJECT</code>.</div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--info\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">🔑</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">How models are configured</div>\n          The <code>model_config.py</code> file maps provider names to environment variables. When you pass <code>--model anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-6</code>, the CLI looks up <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code> and creates the appropriate LangChain model client. Adding a new provider means updating that mapping.\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 2: MCP -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">MCP servers — plugging in external tools</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\"><abbr class=\"term\" data-tip=\"Model Context Protocol — a standard for connecting AI systems to external tools and data sources. Like a USB port for AI.\">MCP</abbr> lets the CLI connect to external tool servers. Think of it like plugging a USB device into your computer — the tool appears as if it were built-in.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"step-cards\">\n        <div class=\"step-card\">\n          <div class=\"step-card__num\">1</div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__title\">The CLI finds MCP configs</div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__desc\">It scans for <code>mcp.json</code> or <code>mcp.yaml</code> files in your project and home directory, plus any path passed via <code>--mcp-config</code>.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"step-card\">\n          <div class=\"step-card__num\">2</div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__title\">Servers are started</div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__desc\">Each server is spawned as a subprocess. The CLI communicates with it over <abbr class=\"term\" data-tip=\"Standard input/output — text streams programs use to communicate. MCP servers receive commands via stdin and respond via stdout.\">stdio</abbr>.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"step-card\">\n          <div class=\"step-card__num\">3</div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__title\">Tools become available to the AI</div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__desc\">The AI sees MCP tools alongside its built-in tools. You can approve or reject individual MCP tool calls in the HITL menu.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 3: Sandboxes -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Sandboxes — running code safely in the cloud</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">By default, the AI runs shell commands on <em>your</em> machine. But you can point it at a remote <span class=\"term\" data-tip=\"A remote Linux machine that runs in a cloud provider's data center. Your code runs there instead of on your local machine.\">sandbox</span> — useful for dangerous operations or cross-platform testing.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"icon-row\">\n        <div class=\"icon-item\">\n          <span class=\"icon-item__emoji\">☁️</span>\n          <span class=\"icon-item__label\">LangSmith</span>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"icon-item\">\n          <span class=\"icon-item__emoji\">🚀</span>\n          <span class=\"icon-item__label\">Agentcore</span>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"icon-item\">\n          <span class=\"icon-item__emoji\">🔷</span>\n          <span class=\"icon-item__label\">Modal</span>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"icon-item\">\n          <span class=\"icon-item__emoji\">🏄</span>\n          <span class=\"icon-item__label\">Daytona</span>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"icon-item\">\n          <span class=\"icon-item__emoji\">🔄</span>\n          <span class=\"icon-item__label\">Runloop</span>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--accent\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">📍</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">Local vs. Remote — the key difference</div>\n          In local mode, the CLI's <code>LocalShellBackend</code> runs commands on your machine. In sandbox mode, the CLI sends commands to a remote Linux VM and streams results back. The UI and UX are nearly identical — but your files are on the remote machine, not yours.\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 4: Quiz -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Check your understanding</h2>\n\n      <div class=\"quiz\" id=\"quiz-module-4\">\n        <div class=\"quiz__question\">You want the AI to have access to your company's internal API docs. What's the best approach?</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__options\">\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"a\">Add them to the <code>AGENTS.md</code> file so the AI always has context</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"b\">Build an MCP server that wraps the API and connect it via <code>--mcp-config</code></button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"c\">Ask the AI to remember the API docs at the start of every conversation</button>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--correct\" data-for=\"b\">Right! An MCP server is the right tool for providing structured, up-to-date access to an external API. The AI can call its tools on demand, and the MCP protocol handles the communication.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"a\">AGENTS.md is for high-level instructions, not large reference data. stuffing API docs in there would bloat the context window.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"c\">That relies on the AI's memory, which is imprecise and context-limited. An MCP server is the structured, reliable solution.</div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n  </div>\n</section>\n\nHTMLEOF\necho \"Modules 2-4 done\"",
